<h3>
<img src="vinesmall.jpg"><font size=5> Cowichan <a name="sweaters">Sweaters</a></font>
</h3>

Among the Northwest Coast Indians there is a long tradition of weaving wool clothing by hand (originally using 
mountain goat hair, later sheep's wool). About a century ago Salish Indian weavers turned this skill towards 
sweater-making, and their distinctive designs have become a native Canadian classic. 
<BR><BR>

<table width=900 cols=2><tr>
<td valign=middle><img align=top src="/images/sweater2.jpg" title="Cowichan sweater" border="0"></td>
<td align=left valign=middle>
<IMG SRC="dot.gif"> <b><A HREF="
http://www.sa-cinn.com/cowichanmain.htm
">Cowichan Indian Clothes</a></b><br>
Hand-knitted Native American sweaters, scarves, and other winter clothes by <A href="http://www.native-languages.org/halkomelem.htm">Coast Salish</a> crafters.
</td></table>

<table width=900 cols=2><tr>
<td valign=middle><img align=top src="/images/sweater.jpg" title="Cowichan sweater" border="0"></td>
<td align=left valign=middle>
<IMG SRC="dot.gif"> <b><A HREF="
http://www.quwutsun.ca/cowichan_sweaters.htm
">Cowichan Sweaters</a></b><br>
This Northwest Indian clothing store sells handmade <A href="http://www.native-languages.org/halkomelem.htm">Cowichan</a> Indian sweaters, mittens, and other woolen clothes.
</td></table>

